					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2005044&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182929" alt="Decibelles" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2005044)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;" >Decibelles</a></span> <span class="odate time_1442868869 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Sep 2015 20:54</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2379508">
									

<p>When developing a loop SCP, you need to expand on it emotionally. This is because you have a strict set of rules and controlling actions dictating what's going on, without leaving much room to expand on it. So every bit counts. I've been guilty of this too, even.</p>
<p>I forget the number, but Dinner With Andrew by ObserverSeptember does this wonderfully by breaking out of the on-rails experience and letting the characters think and feel for themselves while still stuck in an ongoing Hell, and what they learn coming out of it makes it all the more powerful. 176, on the other hand, doesn't let us sympathize with the people trapped; all we know is that their Hell lasts a few brief seconds, gunned down and burnt by an explosion. The looks on their faces (or rather, the words describing their looks) tell us more than any dialog from them could.</p>
<p>Here, you set up a few narrative building blocks, but don't expand upon them in a way to characterize or make the reader emotionally connected. The father is clearly a reality-bender, the two kidnappers deliberately have these nicknames for some reason, and it's the dude trying to lead them astray to save his son. But the dialog hampers the emotional connection by making them sound like bad movie parodies (and no, meaningful name choices don't justify this unless it is an anomalous movie played out in real-life) and making the father sound overwrought. Finally, I can't fathom why the father would want to relive a traumatizing event over and over without doing anything meaningful to stop it. It snaps my suspension of disbelief.</p>
<p>The experiment logs also tell me nothing that you don't already imply and that the audience can't already infer. It takes up space to try and make the article feel more weighty. The amount of content isn't the issue so much as the quality of it.</p>

							</div>

								
