																		Really impressed, good job
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fritzwillie" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(172952); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=172952&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182929" alt="FritzWillie" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=172952)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fritzwillie" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(172952); return false;" >FritzWillie</a></span> <span class="odate time_1442876929 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Sep 2015 23:08</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2379572">
									

<p>Hey man, I really enjoyed your new work. It flowed pretty nicely and was fairly easy to understand. So many of the articles I've been reading lately have been kinda boring or so wordy it's easy to get lost, but I think you really hit the nail on the head.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The concept seems so familiar, where were you inspired? It feels like something I saw out of the outer limits or twilight zone. I really liked the reveal toward the end, where the father pulls the rabbit out of the hat and leaves the reader with more questions than answers. I had an idea for an SCP like this a few years ago, but of course never worked it out. In mine, the spheres of repeating time caused the subjects to unknowingly loop back on each other, where one future event was actually in the past of the previous event for one subject, but in the future of the other. The timeline basically looked like a pretzel. I eventually dropped it because some TV show or some movie at the time came out with the same premise a month or so later.</p>
<p>I like how yours was more straight forward and a lot more easier to understand than mine would have been. However, the 'no one can avoid' fate mechanic at the end felt very forced and a bit unsatisfying. The route I would have gone with was one that made each sphere a portal where Foundation personnel could enter and exit but the subjects couldn't perceive or use. The spheres would open and close at very specific times and personnel could have lasting effects on the subjects' timeline, however personnel who were not present at the final bubble's occurrence where lost forever, perhaps lost to a separate diverging dimension from ours. Then the next day, a whole new dimension is created and the entire process begins over again.</p>
<p>You see, in physics, if you rewind time, you rewind with it, rewinding your actions and your memories. You wouldn't know of future outcomes any more than character in a movie know their outcomes if you rewound them on an old VHS tape. The best option, would to create a separate dimension where an outside influence with knowledge of the future could change the present, then there is statistically, at least one dimension where someone from other (out dimension) intervenes and saves the boy. Our time line we live in now would be a base timeline where you could thread a second timeline through. Out timeline would look like a belt (like the one around your waist) there would be holes in it (the spheres) and the SCP timeline would act like a thread looping in and out of these holes.</p>
<p>Here's where the creepy/sad factor steps in, sure there's a few instances where someone from our timeline intervenes and saves them. But there are many more (one created everyday) where nothing goes unchanged. And each branching dimension is real, with real people in it. There are countless multiverses out there where absolutely nothing changes, and for something to change in one of those created universes, we have do something here in this one. If the wave form never collapses, the Foundation or some other organization would have to spend the rest of eternity righting the same wrong, day after day.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
<em>Please collapse long posts. ~Zyn</em>
							</div>

								
